Poker is a great game to teach object oriented concepts!

The game of poker is relatively simple.  In the standard version of the game (5 card stud), 5 cards are dealt to 2 or more players.  The cards that are dealt to a player is known as a &quot;hand&quot;.  Each hand is evaluated/scored, and then compared with the other player&#39;s hands to find the winner.

In traditional poker, a hand could be one of 10 different categories.  The odds of drawing each hand depends on the combination of cards, frequency, etc.  The probability can be calculated with as a simple combination. Let&#39;s think of the game in terms of objects, let&#39;s start at the lowest levelâ€¦

A &quot;card&quot; is an object.

- Each card has a numeric rank (A, 2, 3, 4.. 10, J, Q, K, A)
- Each card has a suit (heart, spade, club diamond)
- Attributes should be private, without public setter / getters

A &quot;deck&quot; is an object.

- Each deck (you could have multiple decks, depending on the game) is an array of cards.
- When you instantiate a deck, you should build the array list of cards.  You should also &quot;shuffle&quot; the deck (make the order of cards random).
- A method is needed that  will be to &quot;draw&quot; from the deck (return next cardâ€¦ assuming deck is shuffled).
- Build a method to denote how many cards are remaining to be drawn.

A &quot;handpoker&quot; is an object.

- Each hand is an array of cards that are drawn from the deck.
- A common (static) method is needed to judge a single hand.  A similar method (overloaded) will be needed to judge multiple hands (you pass in array of hands, it passes back the winner).
